<worksheet margin="1in" bottom="1.25cm">
    <title>Math 330 Well-Posed Problems</title>

<page>
<exercise>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Do exercise 2 in Section 2.3 of the textbook. Discuss existence of a solution only.
        </p>
    </statement>
</exercise>

<exercise>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Consider Laplace's equation in the plane 
<md>
\Delta u = 0,\ (x,y)\in \Omega,\\
u(x,y) = f(x,y)\  \mbox{for}\ (x,y)\in\partial{\Omega},
</md>
where <m>\Omega</m> is an open, bounded, and connected region in the plane. Show that this problem is stable. That is, show that if <m>|f_1(x,y) - f_2(x,y)|&lt; \epsilon</m> on <m>\partial{\Omega}</m>, then the corresponding solutions to the boundary value problem are separated by at most <m>\epsilon</m> on <m>\Omega</m>. <em>Hint:</em> Use Theorem 1.23 in the book.
        </p>
    </statement>
</exercise>

<exercise>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Use the result of exericse #2 in Section 1.3 of the text to prove that solution to the Cauchy problem for the heat equation (from Section 2.1) are unique.
        </p>
    </statement>
</exercise>
    
<exercise>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Consider the following non-proof of uniqueness of solutions to the Cauchy problem for the heat-equation:
<md>
u_t = ku_xx,\ x\in\mathbb{R},\ t&gt;0
</md>
<md>
u(x,0) = \phi(x).
</md>
<term>Non-Proof:</term> Suppose <m>u_1</m> and <m>u_2</m> are both solutions. Then <m>w = u_1-u_2</m> is a solution to    
<md>
u_t = ku_{xx},\ x\in\mathbb{R},\ t>0 
</md>
<md>
u(x,0) = 0.
</md>
Thus 
<md>
w(x,t) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{4\pi kt}}\int_{\infty}^{\infty} 0\cdot e^{-(x-y)^2/4kt}\,dy,
</md>
which is identically zero. Thus, <m>u_1(x,t) = u_2(x,t)</m> for all <m>x</m> and <m>t</m>.
        </p>
<p>
    <term>Question:</term> Why isn't this a proof of uniqueness?
</p>
    </statement>
</exercise>

</page>            

 


</worksheet>
